{"title":"e*thirteen Expands the Grappler Tire Platform, Adding a Radial Casing","link":"https://bikerumor.com/ethirteen-expands-the-grappler-tire-platform-adding-a-radial-casing/","date":1777474800000,"content":"<p><img src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/T3GP5-109-BK-2-Mopo-Logo-Close-Up-Grass-1536x1024.jpg\" width=\"1536\" height=\"1024\" alt=\"e*thirteens new Grappler tire with radial casing\" /></p>\n<p>There is some more big news regarding e*thirteen’s new mountain bike tires. And, no, they aren’t 32”. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>This announcement concerns the other hot topic in mountain bike tire development: <a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/specialized-grid-gravity-radial-mountain-bike-tires/\">radial rubber</a>. The new radial casing comes on the Grappler tire platform, but e*thirteen didn’t stop there. Today, e*thirteen announces the expansion of the Grappler tire to include not only radial options but also new rubber compounds, treads, casings, and rear-specific tires.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>The New e*thirteen Grappler </h2>\n\n\n\n<figure>\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-2.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1536\" height=\"1025\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-2-1536x1025.jpg\" alt=\"E13 Grappler tire \" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-2-1536x1025.jpg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-2-297x198.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-2-120x80.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-2-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-2-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-2-800x533.jpg 800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-2-720x480.jpg 720w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-2-1349x900.jpg 1349w\" /></a></figure>\n</figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The <a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/ethirteen-grappler-tire-lands-for-dh-and-enduro-mtb/\">Grappler</a> has been around for a few years now. First introduced in 2022, e*thirteen designed the tire with one thing in mind: gravity. The tread was aggressive, with tall shoulder knobs and a 3-2-3 tread pattern for the center lugs.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Clearly, the Grappler was aimed at enduro and DH riders.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>And those were exactly the casing options. e*thirteen offered the Grappler in an Enduro or DH casing, with the choice of their MoPo or Endurance rubber. </p>\n\n\n\n<figure>\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-4.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1536\" height=\"1025\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-4-1536x1025.jpg\" alt=\"E13 Grappler tire 2\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-4-1536x1025.jpg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-4-297x198.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-4-120x80.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-4-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-4-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-4-800x533.jpg 800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-4-720x480.jpg 720w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-4-1349x900.jpg 1349w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-3.jpeg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1536\" height=\"1025\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-3-1536x1025.jpeg\" alt=\"E13 Grappler tire\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-3-1536x1025.jpeg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-3-297x198.jpeg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-3-120x80.jpeg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-3-768x512.jpeg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-3-2048x1366.jpeg 2048w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-3-800x533.jpeg 800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-3-720x480.jpeg 720w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-3-1349x900.jpeg 1349w\" /></a></figure>\n</figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Size was the only option left, with the choice of 29” or 27.5”, with both diameters coming in a 2.5” width.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Building off of that design (literally, it looks like they carried over the same tread pattern), e*thirteen significantly expands the Grappler tire platform. What was one Grappler is now three. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>Before jumping into the new tires, let’s look at the new features seen across (most) the Grappler platform.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Casing and Compounds</h2>\n\n\n\n<p>It’s why you clicked. You saw “radial casing” and needed to see the new offering. Yes, one of the new casings on the e*thirteen Grappler tire is radial. In fact, e*thirteen provides a whole new naming structure for tire casings, moving away from casing names matching intended riding use.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Casings</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure>\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1536\" height=\"1025\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-1536x1025.jpg\" alt=\"E13 Grappler tire\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-1536x1025.jpg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-297x198.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-120x80.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-800x533.jpg 800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-720x480.jpg 720w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Grappler-tire-1349x900.jpg 1349w\" /></a></figure>\n</figure>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Flux GR Radial.</strong> This is, well, the radial casing, and the most aggressive tire in terms of traction and support. e*thirteen uses “super-stiff Dual Apex Sidewall Inserts” in the Flux GR Radial casing. Not only does the casing feature extra bead support to prevent pinch flats, but an overall beefy construction also creates firm sidewalls. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>Extra material increases lateral stability. The big takeaway here is that e*thirteen says you can run normal tire pressures. For comparison, when I use Schwalbe radial tires, I typically run 4-6 PSI higher than with non-radial tires. While e*thirteen recommends a slight increase for significantly rocky trails, they claim tire pressure should remain relatively normal.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>e*thirteen also claims a significant increase in traction. Compared to non-radials, the new Flux GR Radial casing tires have a (claimed) 30% larger contact patch. e*thirteen also claims increased comfort, as the radial casing acts as extra suspension for the bike.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure>\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Flux-GR-casing-scaled.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1536\" height=\"1536\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Flux-GR-casing-1536x1536.jpg\" alt=\"e*thirteen Flux GR casing\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Flux-GR-casing-1536x1536.jpg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Flux-GR-casing-297x297.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Flux-GR-casing-120x120.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Flux-GR-casing-768x768.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Flux-GR-casing-2048x2048.jpg 2048w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Flux-GR-casing-900x900.jpg 900w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Flux-GR-radial-casing-scaled.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1536\" height=\"1536\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Flux-GR-radial-casing-1536x1536.jpg\" alt=\"e*thirteen Flux GR Radial casing\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Flux-GR-radial-casing-1536x1536.jpg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Flux-GR-radial-casing-297x297.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Flux-GR-radial-casing-120x120.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Flux-GR-radial-casing-768x768.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Flux-GR-radial-casing-2048x2048.jpg 2048w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Flux-GR-radial-casing-900x900.jpg 900w\" /></a></figure>\n<figcaption>Radial casing on the right</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Stepping down from radial is the <strong>Flux GR</strong> casing. While this casing isn’t radial and doesn’t see the same Dual Apex Sidewall Inserts, it does feature e*thirteen’s GR Apex inserts. Like the Dual Apex inserts, the GR Apex inserts beef up the sidewalls, increasing lateral stability and overall durability.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Both the Flux GR Radial and Flux GR casings also feature two-ply, 72 TPI construction and Armor Weave sidewall protection. </p>\n\n\n\n<figure>\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Flux-AM-rubber-compound.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1536\" height=\"1025\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Flux-AM-rubber-compound-1536x1025.jpg\" alt=\"new e13 grappler tires\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Flux-AM-rubber-compound-1536x1025.jpg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Flux-AM-rubber-compound-297x198.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Flux-AM-rubber-compound-120x80.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Flux-AM-rubber-compound-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Flux-AM-rubber-compound-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Flux-AM-rubber-compound-800x533.jpg 800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Flux-AM-rubber-compound-720x480.jpg 720w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Flux-AM-rubber-compound-1349x900.jpg 1349w\" /></a></figure>\n</figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Stepping down from there, e*thirteen offers a third casing: <strong>Flux AM</strong>. Tires with Flux AM casing feature two-ply construction with 90 TPI. While this casing doesn’t have either Apex inserts, it does have the Armor Weave sidewall protection.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>For the Flux AM, e*thirteen wanted lighter weight and faster rolling.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Compounds</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure>\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/T3GP5-109-BK-2-Mopo-Logo-Close-Up-Grass-scaled.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1536\" height=\"1024\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/T3GP5-109-BK-2-Mopo-Logo-Close-Up-Grass-1536x1024.jpg\" alt=\"e*thirteens new Grappler tire with radial casing\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/T3GP5-109-BK-2-Mopo-Logo-Close-Up-Grass-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/T3GP5-109-BK-2-Mopo-Logo-Close-Up-Grass-297x198.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/T3GP5-109-BK-2-Mopo-Logo-Close-Up-Grass-120x80.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/T3GP5-109-BK-2-Mopo-Logo-Close-Up-Grass-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/T3GP5-109-BK-2-Mopo-Logo-Close-Up-Grass-2048x1365.jpg 2048w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/T3GP5-109-BK-2-Mopo-Logo-Close-Up-Grass-800x533.jpg 800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/T3GP5-109-BK-2-Mopo-Logo-Close-Up-Grass-720x480.jpg 720w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/T3GP5-109-BK-2-Mopo-Logo-Close-Up-Grass-1350x900.jpg 1350w\" /></a></figure>\n</figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Along with the three casing options, e*thirteen offers two rubber compound options for the new Grappler tires. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>First is their motion potion; the <strong>MoPo</strong> rubber, e*thirteen’s softest and grippiest option. MoPo is constructed with ultra-soft 42a rubber, which is now featured throughout the entire tread. e*thirteen claims this reduces tread rebound and enhances vibration damping. </p>\n\n\n\n<figure>\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Momentum-rubber-compound.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1536\" height=\"1025\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Momentum-rubber-compound-1536x1025.jpg\" alt=\"Momentum rubber compound on new Grappler tires\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Momentum-rubber-compound-1536x1025.jpg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Momentum-rubber-compound-297x198.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Momentum-rubber-compound-120x80.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Momentum-rubber-compound-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Momentum-rubber-compound-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Momentum-rubber-compound-800x533.jpg 800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Momentum-rubber-compound-720x480.jpg 720w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/E13-Momentum-rubber-compound-1349x900.jpg 1349w\" /></a></figure>\n</figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The other compound option (no more “Endurance”) will be e*thirteen’s <strong>Momentum</strong> rubber. Momentum is a dual-compound design, with a firmer 50a rubber in the center and the soft 42a rubber at the shoulders. e*thirteen says Momentum provides great longevity without sacrificing performance, and is an ideal choice for rear tires and eMTBs.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>The Expanded Grappler Lineup</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure>\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-TR-Grappler-Grappler-RS-Tires-scaled.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1536\" height=\"1024\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-TR-Grappler-Grappler-RS-Tires-1536x1024.jpg\" alt=\"Three new Grappler tires from e*thirteen\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-TR-Grappler-Grappler-RS-Tires-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-TR-Grappler-Grappler-RS-Tires-297x198.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-TR-Grappler-Grappler-RS-Tires-120x80.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-TR-Grappler-Grappler-RS-Tires-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-TR-Grappler-Grappler-RS-Tires-2048x1365.jpg 2048w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-TR-Grappler-Grappler-RS-Tires-800x533.jpg 800w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-TR-Grappler-Grappler-RS-Tires-720x480.jpg 720w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-TR-Grappler-Grappler-RS-Tires-1350x900.jpg 1350w\" /></a></figure>\n</figure>\n\n\n\n<p>So now e*thirteen’s Grappler is actually a family of three tires. Well, three tread patterns. Well, sort of two…</p>\n\n\n\n<p>In the press material, they referred to the range as “simplified,” which I think is quite a stretch. Just in case I miss anything, I will include a chart that helps line up all the new options. Now, here goes my attempt to explain the new tire offerings.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>3 New Tires</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure>\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-Tire-Matrix-.png\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1536\" height=\"556\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-Tire-Matrix--1536x556.png\" alt=\"Grappler Tire Matrix\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-Tire-Matrix--1536x556.png 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-Tire-Matrix--297x107.png 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-Tire-Matrix--120x43.png 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-Tire-Matrix--768x278.png 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-Tire-Matrix--2048x741.png 2048w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-Tire-Matrix--1600x579.png 1600w\" /></a></figure>\n</figure>\n\n\n\n<p>First, there is the tire that will remain the <strong>Grappler</strong>. This is the aforementioned tire that appears to use the same (or very similar) 3-2-3 tread pattern as its predecessor. It is e*thirteen’s gravity cornerstone (for tires, at least) and offers the most options in the lineup.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure>\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Tire-Tread_Grappler.png\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"8334\" height=\"8334\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Tire-Tread_Grappler.png\" alt=\"e13 Grappler tire info chart\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Tire-Tread_Grappler.png 8334w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Tire-Tread_Grappler-297x297.png 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Tire-Tread_Grappler-120x120.png 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Tire-Tread_Grappler-768x768.png 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Tire-Tread_Grappler-900x900.png 900w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-tread-scaled.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1536\" height=\"1536\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-tread-1536x1536.jpg\" alt=\"Grappler tread\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-tread-1536x1536.jpg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-tread-297x297.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-tread-120x120.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-tread-768x768.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-tread-2048x2048.jpg 2048w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-tread-900x900.jpg 900w\" /></a></figure>\n</figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The Grappler’s intended use stretches from trail and all-mountain to DH and eMTB. The use will depend on the casing chosen, which the Grappler provides all three Flux casing options. You also have the choice of MoPo or Momentum rubber compounds, making the tire ideal for the front or the rear. e*thirteen says it does best in loose, wet, and/or technical terrain.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Moving on from the Grappler is the <strong>Grappler RS</strong>. I’m assuming here that “RS” means “Rear Specific” because e*thirteen says this is a rear-specific tire. What makes it a rear tire?</p>\n\n\n\n<figure>\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Tire-Tread_Grappler-RS.png\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"8334\" height=\"8334\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Tire-Tread_Grappler-RS.png\" alt=\"e13 Grappler tire info chart\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Tire-Tread_Grappler-RS.png 8334w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Tire-Tread_Grappler-RS-297x297.png 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Tire-Tread_Grappler-RS-120x120.png 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Tire-Tread_Grappler-RS-768x768.png 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Tire-Tread_Grappler-RS-900x900.png 900w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-RS-tread-scaled.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1536\" height=\"1536\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-RS-tread-1536x1536.jpg\" alt=\"Grappler RS tread\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-RS-tread-1536x1536.jpg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-RS-tread-297x297.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-RS-tread-120x120.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-RS-tread-768x768.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-RS-tread-2048x2048.jpg 2048w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-RS-tread-900x900.jpg 900w\" /></a></figure>\n</figure>\n\n\n\n<p>e*thirteen created the Grappler RS with a “rear-optimized 2-2-2” tread pattern, adding tall and steeply ramped center knobs. This not only improves braking traction but also increases rolling speed. Oh, and the Grappler RS only comes in a 27.5”.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>With the Grappler RS, the only casing options are the Flux GR Radial and Flux GR. The rear tire is available in both rubber compounds and is intended for enduro, DH, and eMTBs.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Lastly, we have the <strong>Grappler TR</strong>. As far as tread goes, it looks like the Grappler RS, but e*thirteen says it has a lower profile. But that means faster rolling and lightweight. </p>\n\n\n\n<figure>\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Tire-Tread_Grappler-TR.png\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"8334\" height=\"8334\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Tire-Tread_Grappler-TR.png\" alt=\"e13 Grappler TR tire info chart\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Tire-Tread_Grappler-TR.png 8334w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Tire-Tread_Grappler-TR-297x297.png 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Tire-Tread_Grappler-TR-120x120.png 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Tire-Tread_Grappler-TR-768x768.png 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Tire-Tread_Grappler-TR-900x900.png 900w\" /></a></figure>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-TR-tread-scaled.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1536\" height=\"1536\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-TR-tread-1536x1536.jpg\" alt=\"Grappler TR tread\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-TR-tread-1536x1536.jpg 1536w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-TR-tread-297x297.jpg 297w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-TR-tread-120x120.jpg 120w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-TR-tread-768x768.jpg 768w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-TR-tread-2048x2048.jpg 2048w, https://bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Grappler-TR-tread-900x900.jpg 900w\" /></a></figure>\n</figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The Grappler TR also sees the fewest choice options. While the tire was intended for front or rear and is available in 29” or 27.5”, that is where the choices stop. No radial casing, just the Flux AM casing, and only the Momentum Compound rubber. </p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Pricing and Details</h2>\n\n\n\n<p>In the press material, e*thirteen also used the term “affordable.” That, I can agree with. The range starts at $60 and tops out at $80. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>Not bad considering some tires are double that.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>If you didn’t see them in the chart above, here are some weights and prices for the new lineup:</p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Grappler</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<ul>\n<li>Flux GR Radial casing, 1,425g (27.5) / 1,510g (29), $79.95</li>\n\n\n\n<li>Flux GR casing, 1,445g (27.5) / 1,520g (29), $69.95</li>\n\n\n\n<li>Flux AM casing, 1,255g (27.5) / 1,305g (29), $59.95</li>\n</ul>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Grappler RS</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<ul>\n<li>Flux GR Radial casing, 1,460g (27.5), $79.95</li>\n\n\n\n<li>Flux GR casing, 1,460g (27.5), $69.95</li>\n</ul>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Grappler TR</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<ul>\n<li>Flux AM casing, 1,255g (27.5) / 1,310 (29), $59.95</li>\n</ul>\n\n\n\n<p><em><a href=\"https://www.ethirteen.com/\">ethirteen.com</a></em></p>\n<p>The post <a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/ethirteen-expands-the-grappler-tire-platform-adding-a-radial-casing/\">e*thirteen Expands the Grappler Tire Platform, Adding a Radial Casing</a> appeared first on <a href=\"https://bikerumor.com\">Bikerumor</a>.</p>","author":"Travis Reill","siteTitle":"Bikerumor","siteHash":"49f427af0a926f4232eb837006841d7242e153e3afbb590f32e4b104ea3e2718","entryHash":"354d16ab5ae730d000c4dec4de6f79b87366dd9ccef417d94ca488f8ec4b79fe","category":"Cycling"}